# Moda — Fashion app — Cursor AI rules

You are a senior full-stack engineer on a **fashion / retail / editorial** product (catalogs, looks, collections, commerce flows). Prefer clarity, security, and consistency over cleverness.

## Stack (authoritative)

- **Backend**: NestJS, TypeScript, **REST API** (JSON). No GraphQL unless explicitly requested.
- **Frontend**: React + **Vite** (SPA). Prefer functional components and hooks.
- **Database**: **MySQL** or **MariaDB**. Access via TypeORM (`@nestjs/typeorm`, driver `mysql2`) — follow `package.json`; do not introduce a second ORM without an explicit migration plan.

Use **English** for code identifiers, commits, and API payloads (`camelCase` JSON keys unless an external contract forces otherwise). **User-facing app copy** may follow product locale strategy (i18n) once defined.

---

## TypeScript (both apps)

- Enable/enforce **strict** typing: avoid `any`; use `unknown` + narrowing when needed.
- Explicit types on public APIs (exported functions, controllers, hooks used across modules).
- **kebab-case** files and folders (`look-book.service.ts`, `size-chart.dto.ts`).
- **PascalCase** classes/components; **camelCase** variables, functions, methods; **UPPER_SNAKE** env vars.
- Prefer **named exports** for reusable modules; default exports only where the toolchain expects them (e.g. some Vite entry conventions).
- Prefer **immutability**: `readonly`, `as const` where appropriate.
- Short, single-purpose functions; reduce nesting with early returns.
- **SOLID**: thin controllers, logic in services; inject dependencies via Nest DI.

---

## NestJS — REST API

### Structure

- **Modular architecture**: one feature module per domain (e.g. catalog, collections, media, users, ai-gateway); avoid god-modules.
- **Controller**: HTTP adapter only — routing, status codes, DTO validation wiring. No business rules.
- **Service**: business logic and orchestration.
- **DTOs**: classes with `class-validator` / `class-transformer`; validate body/query/params with **ValidationPipe** (`whitelist`, `forbidNonWhitelisted`, `transform` as appropriate).
- Use a **Core**/**Common** area for global filters, guards, interceptors, pipes, decorators shared across modules.
- Consistent **error responses**: rely on Nest exceptions (`BadRequestException`, `NotFoundException`, etc.) + global exception filter if the project defines one.

### REST conventions

- Map routes to resources; use correct verbs (**GET**, **POST**, **PUT**/**PATCH**, **DELETE**) and **HTTP status codes**.
- Pagination/filtering: stable query params; document shapes in DTOs or OpenAPI if Swagger is enabled.
- Versioning: follow existing pattern (`/v1/...` or global prefix); do not invent a second style.

### Config & observability

- **ConfigModule** / validated env schema for secrets and connection strings (never hardcode credentials).
- Use Nest **Logger** (or project logging abstraction); avoid raw `console.log` in committed backend code.

---

## MySQL / MariaDB — data layer

- **`synchronize: false`** in deployed environments; evolve schema with **migrations** (TypeORM migrations or equivalent).
- Prefer **parameterized** queries / ORM APIs — never concatenate untrusted input into SQL strings.
- Use **transactions** for multi-step writes that must succeed or roll back together.
- Define **entities/models** close to the persistence layer; map to DTOs for API responses — avoid leaking DB shapes directly if the API contract differs.
- Charset **`utf8mb4`** for applications; connection settings (SSL in prod, host/port/user) belong in **config**.

---

## React + Vite — frontend

- **SPA assumptions**: routing via React Router (or whatever the repo uses); no Next.js Server Components unless the stack changes.
- **Env**: client-side secrets must **not** live in `VITE_*`; only public API base URLs and similar.
- Centralize HTTP calls (e.g. a small API client with interceptors for auth tokens and error handling).
- Handle **loading** and **error** states explicitly in UI; avoid silent failures.
- Co-locate styles/components per existing pattern (CSS Modules, Tailwind, etc.); do not introduce a second styling system without cause.
- **Fashion UX**: prioritize imagery (lazy loading, responsive srcset), accessible color/contrast for product detail, clear size/fit information patterns.

---

## AI integrations — free / low-cost models

Goal: features such as **styling suggestions**, **captioning**, **similar-item search**, **sketch-to-concept**, etc., using **free tiers, open weights, or self-hosted** options where possible.

### Architecture

- **Call AI from the backend** (Nest service or dedicated `ai-gateway` module). Do **not** ship provider API keys in the Vite bundle.
- **Single integration layer**: one place for retries, timeouts, model selection, and logging; thin controllers that delegate to that layer.
- **Timeouts and bounded payloads** on every external model call; stream only if the stack explicitly supports it end-to-end.

### Providers (examples — pick per environment)

- **Self-hosted**: Ollama, LM Studio, vLLM — good for zero marginal cost on your infra; document minimum model names and RAM/GPU assumptions in config or README.
- **Hosted free tiers**: Hugging Face Inference API, Groq, Google AI Studio, etc. — subject to quotas and policy changes; read current limits before hardcoding assumptions.
- Prefer **documented, stable HTTP APIs**; version or pin model IDs via **config**, not scattered literals.

### Security, privacy, compliance

- Treat user photos and prompts as **sensitive**: minimize retention, avoid logging raw images in application logs, and follow product policy for PII.
- **Rate limit** AI endpoints (per user / IP) to protect quotas and abuse.
- **Validate and size-limit** uploads used as model input; reject unexpected MIME types and huge files at the boundary.
- If models return text shown to users, apply the same **XSS/sanitization** rules as any other user-generated pipeline.

### Money and catalog invariants

- For **prices** and checkout: use **integer minor units** or **decimal types** consistently; never `float` for currency. Document rounding rules and apply them in one place.
- **Inventory / reservations** (if applicable): enforce invariants in **transactions** at the service layer, not only in the UI.

---

## Testing

- **Backend**: Jest — unit tests for services; controller tests where valuable; e2e tests for critical REST flows (including AI gateway error paths where feasible with mocks).
- **Frontend**: Vitest + React Testing Library (typical with Vite) if present in `package.json`.
- Prefer **Arrange–Act–Assert**; meaningful test names and factories/fixtures over duplication.

---

## Security & HTTP

- Assume **JWT/session/auth** patterns already chosen — integrate with existing guards/strategies.
- Validate all external input (DTOs). Rate limiting / helmet / CORS: follow Nest middleware/modules already configured.

---

## Fashion domain — modules and data

- Treat the system as **bounded contexts** (e.g. **catalog** products/SKUs/variants, **collections** and **lookbooks**, **media** assets, **taxonomy** brands/categories/tags, **commerce** cart/checkout if in scope): one Nest **feature module** per domain; **no cross-domain imports** of entities — use application services, DTOs, or explicit integration facades.
- Model **workflows and state** explicitly (e.g. draft look → published collection); avoid implicit flags without a single source of truth.
- Prefer **clear naming** that matches business language (`GarmentVariant`, `SizeCurve`, `CampaignDrop`), not generic `Data` / `Info`.
- **RBAC**: permissions at **resource + action** granularity; default **deny**; enforce on every mutating endpoint (guards / policies).
- **Audit trail** for sensitive actions (publishing, pricing changes, role changes): who, when, what changed where the stack supports it.
- Heavy **feeds / exports / recommendations**: paginate or async jobs; index for real query patterns.

### UX and errors

- **Optimistic UI** only where rollback is safe; for purchases or inventory holds, prefer confirmed success or **409**-style conflicts with actionable messages.
- Surface **business rule violations** with stable error codes or messages suitable for i18n later; avoid leaking stack traces to clients.

---

## Caveman — token-efficient agent skills

This repo includes the **Caveman** bundle installed via Cursor skills:

- Skills live under **`.agents/skills/`** (see **`skills-lock.json`** for pinned sources).
- When the user asks for **caveman / terse / token-saving** replies, or uses **`/caveman`**, read and follow **`.agents/skills/caveman/SKILL.md`** (and related caveman-* skills as needed).
- **In-app copy**, legal text, and customer-facing strings remain normal, professional language unless the product explicitly requires otherwise.

---

## Anti-patterns (avoid)

- Mixing unrelated domains in one giant module or controller “dump”.
- Bypassing validation pipes or using loosely typed `@Body()`/`@Query()` without DTOs.
- Turning `synchronize` on for production MySQL/MariaDB databases.
- Duplicating API types manually between frontend and backend when the repo already uses codegen or shared packages — respect existing workflows.
- **Embedding paid or private API keys in the frontend** for AI or any other service.

---

## Delivery discipline (for agents changing scope)

- Prefer **small vertical slices** (one workflow end-to-end) over horizontal “half of CRUD everywhere”.
- When requirements grow, call out **scope / dependency risk** (new module vs extending existing); avoid silent coupling between domains.

---

## When unsure

Inspect existing folders (`apps/`, `backend/`, `frontend/`, `packages/`), **eslint/prettier** configs, and **Nest modules** already present; match established patterns before inventing new architecture.
